    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-07-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-07-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="687"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d687">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.3531/154</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Acting Secretary of State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-07-14">July 14,
                            1933</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Argentine Ambassador called me on the telephone to say that he was in receipt
                    of a telegram from his Government expressing satisfaction at the desire of the
                    United States to explore the possibilities of a new trade agreement between the
                    two countries. His telegram coincided with the telegram which we have received
                    this morning from our Embassy in Buenos Aires, No. 67.</p>
                <p>Mr. Espil said, however, that he was going to ask his Government to send one or
                    two experts to assist him in the preliminary conversations. These experts are
                    now in London with Le Breton and could easily be here in the course of three or
                    four weeks. The Ambassador did not wish to begin his conversations until the
                    arrival of these experts. He referred to them as men without any particular rank
                    but as having the information which he would require.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
